    bodyEn: [
      'It happens like this: the day seems to be going fine, and suddenly — sharply, strongly — you want to smoke. As if out of nowhere. But a craving almost never comes out of nowhere. Look closer, and there is almost always something else underneath it. And there is a simple way to catch that "something".',
      'It is called HALT — from the first letters of four words. These are four states in which cravings spike sharply: Hungry, Angry, Lonely, Tired. The dependence is cunning: it uses any of these gaps to push the thought of a cigarette through.',
      'So the moment you want to smoke, do not reach straight for the pack. Pause for ten seconds and calmly run through the list, one by one: am I hungry? am I angry or irritated? am I lonely? am I tired? Very often a "yes" turns up in one of the four — and there it is, the real cause. The cigarette was simply masking it.',
      'Here is how it looks in life. You skipped lunch, by five o\'clock your blood sugar dropped — and you "suddenly" wanted to smoke. In fact you wanted to eat. Or a meeting got you worked up, everything is boiling inside — your hand reaches for a cigarette, because smoking was for years your way to "let off steam".',
      'And here is the key thing to grasp: a cigarette does not actually meet any of those four needs. Hungry — eat properly, do not "smother" hunger with smoke. Angry — release the emotion for real: move, walk fast, write down everything you think, say it out loud. Lonely — text someone close, call them, do not sit alone. Tired — let yourself rest or sleep, even twenty minutes.',
      'A cigarette does not feed you, does not calm anger, does not cure loneliness and gives no rest. It only mutes the body signal for a few minutes — and then the signal returns, the need is still there, only now with an added dose of nicotine.',
      'So HALT is not just an acronym, it is a working habit. Meet the real need — eat, cool down, talk, rest — and you will find the craving often dissolves on its own, with no fight at all. You gave the body what it actually needed.',
    ],
